# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fargo-trucks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:fargo-trucks/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The earliest recorded human presence in modern-day Argentina dates back to the Paleolithic period.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Inca Empire expanded to the northwest of the country in pre-Columbian times.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The modern country has its roots in Spanish colonisation of the region during the 16th century.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina rose as the successor state of the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, a Spanish overseas viceroyalty founded in 1776.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Argentine Declaration of Independence on July 9 of 1816 and the Argentine War of Independence (1810–1825) were followed by an extended civil war that lasted until 1880, culminating in the country's reorganisation as a federation.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The country thereafter enjoyed relative peace and stability, with several subsequent waves of European immigration, mainly of Italians and Spaniards, influencing its culture and demography.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The National Autonomist Party dominated national politics in the period called the Conservative Republic, from 1880 until the 1916 elections.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Great Depression led to the first coup d'état in 1930 led by José Félix Uriburu, beginning the so-called "Infamous Decade" (1930–1943).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Following the death of President Juan Perón in 1974, his widow and vice president, Isabel Perón, ascended to the presidency, before being overthrown in the final coup in 1976.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The following military junta persecuted and murdered thousands of political critics, activists, and leftists in the Dirty War, a period of state terrorism and civil unrest that lasted until the election of Raúl Alfonsín as president in 1983.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina is a regional power, and retains its historic status as a middle power in international affairs.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] A major non-NATO ally of the United States, Argentina is a developing country with the second-highest HDI (human development index) in Latin America after Chile.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Its economy is the second-largest in South America, and it is a member of G-15 and G20.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina is also a founding member of the United Nations, World Bank, World Trade Organization, Mercosur, Community of Latin American and Caribbean States and the Organization of Ibero-American States.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The description of the region by the word *Argentina* has been found on a Venetian map in 1536.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In English, the name *Argentina* comes from the Spanish language; however, the naming itself is not Spanish, but Italian.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] *Argentina* (masculine *argentino*) means in Italian '(made) of silver, silver coloured', derived from the Latin *argentum* for silver.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In Italian, the adjective or the proper noun is often used in an autonomous way as a substantive and replaces it and it is said *l'Argentina*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The name *Argentina* was probably first given by the Venetian and Genoese navigators, such as Giovanni Caboto.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In Spanish and Portuguese, the words for 'silver' are respectively *plata* and *prata* and '(made) of silver' is *plateado* and *prateado*, although *argento* for 'silver' and *argentado* for 'covered in silver' exist in Spanish.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] *Argentina* was first associated with the silver mountains legend, widespread among the first European explorers of the La Plata Basin.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The first written use of the name in Spanish can be traced to *La Argentina*, a 1602 poem by Martín del Barco Centenera describing the region.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Although "Argentina" was already in common usage by the 18th century, the country was formally named "Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata" by the Spanish Empire, and "United Provinces of the Río de la Plata" after independence.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The 1826 constitution included the first use of the name "Argentine Republic" in legal documents.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The name "Argentine Confederation" was also commonly used and was formalised in the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1860 a presidential decree settled the country's name as "Argentine Republic", and that year's constitutional amendment ruled all the names since 1810 as legally valid.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In English, the country was traditionally called "the Argentine", mimicking the typical Spanish usage *la Argentina* and perhaps resulting from a mistaken shortening of the longer name "Argentine Republic".
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] "The Argentine" fell out of fashion during the mid-to-late 20th century, and now the country is referred to as "Argentina".
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Evidence suggests that humans inhabited parts of what is now Argentina as early as 21,000 years ago.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 2015, fossilised bones of a large, extinct armoured mammal called *Neosclerocalyptus* were unearthed near Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] These bones bore cut marks indicative of butchering with stone tools, implying human activity during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Further south, the Piedra Museo site in Santa Cruz Province has yielded human remains and artifacts dating back approximately 11,000 years.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Discoveries at this site include spearheads associated with extinct megafauna such as *Mylodon* and *Hippidion*, highlighting the advanced hunting practices of early inhabitants.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Another significant site is the Cueva de las Manos (Cave of the Hands), also located in Santa Cruz.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] This cave features stencilled handprints and hunting scenes created between 7,300 BC and 700 AD, offering insights into the lives of early hunter-gatherer communities.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Until the period of European colonisation, Argentina was relatively sparsely populated by a wide number of diverse cultures with different social organisations, which can be divided into three main groups.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The first group were basic hunters and food gatherers without the development of pottery, such as the Selkʼnam and Yaghan in the extreme south.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The second group were advanced hunters and food gatherers, who included the Puelche, Querandí and Serranos in the centre-east; and the Tehuelche in the south, all of them conquered by the Mapuche spreading from Chile, and the Qom and Wichi in the north.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Europeans first arrived in the region with the 1502 voyage of Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Spanish navigators Juan Díaz de Solís and Sebastian Cabot visited the territory that is now Argentina in 1516 and 1526, respectively.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1536 Pedro de Mendoza founded the small settlement of Buenos Aires, which was abandoned in 1541.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Further colonisation efforts came from Paraguay—establishing the Governorate of the Río de la Plata—Peru and Chile.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Francisco de Aguirre founded Santiago del Estero in 1553.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Londres was founded in 1558; Mendoza, in 1561; San Juan, in 1562; San Miguel de Tucumán, in 1565.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Juan de Garay founded Santa Fe in 1573 and the same year Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera set up Córdoba.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Garay went further south to re-found Buenos Aires in 1580.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires repelled two ill-fated British invasions in 1806 and 1807.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The ideas of the Age of Enlightenment and the example of the first Atlantic Revolutions generated criticism of the absolutist monarchy that ruled the country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] As in the rest of Spanish America, the overthrow of Ferdinand VII during the Peninsular War created great concern.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Beginning a process from which Argentina was to emerge as successor state to the Viceroyalty, the 1810 May Revolution replaced the viceroy Baltasar Hidalgo de Cisneros with the First Junta, a new government in Buenos Aires made up from locals.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In the first clashes of the Independence War the Junta crushed a royalist counter-revolution in Córdoba, but failed to overcome those of the Banda Oriental, Upper Peru and Paraguay, which later became independent states.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The French-Argentine Hippolyte Bouchard then brought his fleet to wage war against Spain overseas and attacked Spanish California, Spanish Peru and Spanish Philippines.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He secured the allegiance of escaped Filipinos in San Blas who defected from the Spanish to join the Argentine navy, due to common Argentine and Philippine grievances against Spanish colonisation.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Jose de San Martin's brother, Juan Fermín de San Martín, was already in the Philippines and drumming up revolutionary fervour prior to this.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] At a later date, the Argentine sign of Inca origin, the Sun of May was adopted as a symbol by the Filipinos in the Philippine Revolution against Spain.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He also secured the diplomatic recognition of Argentina from King Kamehameha I of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Historian Pacho O'Donnell affirms that Hawaii was the first state that recognised Argentina's independence.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He was finally arrested in 1819 by Chilean patriots.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Revolutionaries split into two antagonist groups: the Centralists and the Federalists—a move that would define Argentina's first decades of independence.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Assembly of the Year XIII appointed Gervasio Antonio de Posadas as Argentina's first Supreme Director.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] On 9 July 1816, the Congress of Tucumán formalised the Declaration of Independence, which is now celebrated as Independence Day, a national holiday.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] One year later General Martín Miguel de Güemes stopped royalists on the north.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] General José de San Martín joined Bernardo O'Higgins, and they led a combined army across the Andes and secured the independence of Chile; then it was sent by O'Higgins orders to the Spanish stronghold of Lima and proclaimed the independence of Peru.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1819 Buenos Aires enacted a centralist constitution that was soon abrogated by federalists.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Some of the most important figures of Argentine independence made a proposal known as the Inca plan of 1816, which proposed that the United Provinces of the Río de la Plata (modern-day Argentina) should be a monarchy, led by a descendant of the Inca.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Juan Bautista Túpac Amaru (half-brother of Túpac Amaru II) was proposed as monarch.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Some examples of those who supported this proposal were Manuel Belgrano, José de San Martín and Martín Miguel de Güemes.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Congress of Tucumán finally decided to reject the Inca plan, creating instead a republican, centralist state.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The 1820 Battle of Cepeda, fought between the Centralists and the Federalists, resulted in the *end of the Supreme Director rule*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1826 Buenos Aires enacted another centralist constitution, with Bernardino Rivadavia being appointed as the first president of the country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] However, the interior provinces soon rose against him, forced his resignation and discarded the constitution.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Centralists and Federalists resumed the civil war; the latter prevailed and formed the Argentine Confederation in 1831, led by Juan Manuel de Rosas.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] During his regime he faced a French blockade (1838–1840), the War of the Confederation (1836–1839), and an Anglo-French blockade (1845–1850), but remained undefeated and prevented further loss of national territory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] His trade restriction policies, however, angered the interior provinces and in 1852 Justo José de Urquiza, another powerful caudillo, beat him out of power.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] As the new president of the Confederation, Urquiza enacted the liberal and federal 1853 Constitution.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires seceded but was forced back into the Confederation after being defeated in the 1859 Battle of Cepeda.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Overpowering Urquiza in the 1861 Battle of Pavón, Bartolomé Mitre secured Buenos Aires' predominance and was elected as the first president of the reunified country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He was followed by Domingo Faustino Sarmiento and Nicolás Avellaneda; these three presidencies set up the basis of the modern Argentine State.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Starting with Julio Argentino Roca in 1880, ten consecutive federal governments emphasised liberal economic policies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The massive wave of European immigration they promoted—second only to the United States'—led to a near-reinvention of Argentine society and economy that by 1908 had placed the country as the seventh wealthiest developed nation in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Fostered by a new public, compulsory, free and secular education system, literacy quickly increased from 22% to 65%, a level higher than most Latin American nations would reach even fifty years later.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Furthermore, real GDP grew so fast that despite the huge immigration influx, per capita income between 1862 and 1920 went from 67% of developed country levels to 100%: In 1865, Argentina was already one of the top 25 nations by per capita income.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] By 1908, it had surpassed Denmark, Canada and the Netherlands to reach 7th place—behind Switzerland, New Zealand, Australia, the United States, the United Kingdom and Belgium.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina's per capita income was 70% higher than Italy's, 90% higher than Spain's, 180% higher than Japan's and 400% higher than Brazil's.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Despite these unique achievements, the country was slow to meet its original goals of industrialisation: after the steep development of capital-intensive local industries in the 1920s, a significant part of the manufacturing sector remained labour-intensive in the 1930s.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Between 1878 and 1884, the so-called Conquest of the Desert occurred, with the purpose of tripling the Argentine territory by means of the constant confrontations between natives and Criollos in the border, and the appropriation of the indigenous territories.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The first conquest consisted of a series of military incursions into the Pampa and Patagonian territories dominated by the indigenous peoples, distributing them among the members of the Sociedad Rural Argentina, financiers of the expeditions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The conquest of Chaco lasted up to the end of the century, since its full ownership of the national economic system only took place when the mere extraction of wood and tannin was replaced by the production of cotton.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Argentine government considered indigenous people as inferior beings, without the same rights as Criollos and Europeans.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1912, President Roque Sáenz Peña enacted universal and secret male suffrage, which allowed Hipólito Yrigoyen, leader of the Radical Civic Union (or UCR), to win the 1916 election.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He enacted social and economic reforms and extended assistance to small farms and businesses.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War I.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The second administration of Yrigoyen faced an economic crisis, precipitated by the Great Depression.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1930, Yrigoyen was ousted from power by the military led by José Félix Uriburu.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Although Argentina remained among the fifteen richest countries until mid-century, this coup d'état marked the start of the steady economic and social decline that pushed the country back into underdevelopment.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Uriburu ruled for two years; then Agustín Pedro Justo was elected in a fraudulent election and signed a controversial treaty with the United Kingdom.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War II, a decision that had full British support but was rejected by the United States after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1943 a military coup d'état led by General Arturo Rawson toppled the constitutional government of Ramón Castillo.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Under pressure from the United States, later Argentina declared war on the Axis Powers (on 27 March 1945, roughly a month before the end of World War II in Europe).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] During the Rawson dictatorship a relatively unknown military colonel named Juan Perón was named head of the Labour Department.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón quickly managed to climb the political ladder, being named defence minister in 1944.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Being perceived as a political threat by rivals in the military and the conservative camp, he was forced to resign in 1945, and was arrested days later.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He was finally released under mounting pressure from both his base and several allied unions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He later became president after a landslide victory over the UCR in the 1946 general election as the Labour candidate.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Labour Party (later renamed Justicialist Party), the most powerful and influential party in Argentine history, came into power with the rise of Juan Perón to the presidency in 1946.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He nationalised strategic industries and services, improved wages and working conditions, paid the full external debt and claimed he achieved nearly full employment.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He pushed Congress to enact women's suffrage in 1947, and developed a system of social assistance for the most vulnerable sectors of society.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The economy began to decline in 1950 due in part to government expenditures and the protectionist economic policies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He also engaged in a campaign of political suppression.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Anyone who was perceived to be a political dissident or potential rival was subject to threats, physical violence and harassment.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Argentine intelligentsia, the middle-class, university students, and professors were seen as particularly troublesome.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón fired over 2,000 university professors and faculty members from all major public education institutions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón tried to bring most trade and labour unions under his thumb, regularly resorting to violence when needed.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] For instance, the meat-packers union leader, Cipriano Reyes, organised strikes in protest against the government after elected labour movement officials were forcefully replaced by Peronist puppets from the Peronist Party.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Reyes was soon arrested on charges of terrorism, though the allegations were never substantiated.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Reyes, who was never formally charged, was tortured in prison for five years and only released after the regime's downfall in 1955.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] His wife Eva Perón, who played a critical role in the party, died of cancer in 1952.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] As the economy continued to tank, Perón started losing popular support, and came to be seen as a threat to the national process.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Navy took advantage of Perón's withering political power, and bombed the Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón survived the attack, but a few months later, during the Liberating Revolution coup, he was deposed and went into exile in Spain.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The new head of State, Pedro Eugenio Aramburu, proscribed Peronism and banned the party from any future elections.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Arturo Frondizi from the UCR won the 1958 general election.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He encouraged investment to achieve energetic and industrial self-sufficiency, reversed a chronic trade deficit and lifted the ban on Peronism; yet his efforts to stay on good terms with both the Peronists and the military earned him the rejection of both and a new coup forced him out.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Amidst the political turmoil, Senate leader José María Guido reacted swiftly and applied anti-power vacuum legislation, ascending to the presidency himself; elections were repealed and Peronism was prohibited once again.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Elected in 1963, Arturo Illia presided over a period of broad economic expansion until his 1966 ousting by a military coup led by General Juan Carlos Onganía.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] This Argentine Revolution established a long-term military dictatorship intended to rule indefinitely.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Following several years of military rule, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse was appointed president by the military junta in 1971.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Under increasing political pressure for the return of democracy, Lanusse called for elections in 1973.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón was banned from running but the Peronist party was allowed to participate.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The presidential elections were won by Perón's surrogate candidate, Hector Cámpora, a left-wing Peronist, who took office on 25 May 1973.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] A month later, in June, Perón returned from Spain.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] One of Cámpora's first presidential actions was to grant amnesty to members of organisations that had carried out political assassinations and terrorist attacks, and to those who had been tried and sentenced to prison by judges.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Cámpora's months-long tenure in government was beset by political and social unrest.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Over 600 social conflicts, strikes, and factory occupations took place within a single month.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Even though far-left terrorist organisations had suspended their armed struggle, their joining with the participatory democracy process was interpreted as a direct threat by the Peronist right-wing faction.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Amid a state of political, social, and economic upheaval, Cámpora and Vice President Vicente Solano Lima resigned in July 1973, calling for new elections, but this time with Perón as the Justicialist Party nominee.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón won the election with his wife Isabel Perón as vice president.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón's third term was marked by escalating conflict between left and right-wing factions within the Peronist party, as well as the return of armed terror guerrilla groups such as the Guevarist ERP, leftist Peronist Montoneros, and the state-backed far-right Triple A.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] After a series of heart attacks and signs of pneumonia in 1974, Perón's health deteriorated quickly.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He suffered a final heart attack on Monday, 1 July 1974, and died at 13:15.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] After his death, Isabel Perón, his wife and vice president, succeeded him in office.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] During her presidency, a military junta, along with the Peronists' far-right fascist faction, once again became the *de facto* head of state.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón served as President of Argentina from 1974 until 1976, when she was ousted by the military.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Her short presidency was marked by the collapse of Argentine political and social systems, leading to a constitutional crisis that paved the way for a decade of instability, left-wing terrorist guerrilla attacks, and state-sponsored terrorism.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The "Dirty War" (Spanish: *Guerra Sucia*) was part of Operation Condor, which included the participation of other right-wing dictatorships in the Southern Cone.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Victims of the violence in Argentina alone included an estimated 15,000 to 30,000 left-wing activists and militants, including trade unionists, students, journalists, Marxists, Peronist guerrillas, and alleged sympathisers.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Most of the victims were casualties of state terrorism.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The opposing guerrillas' victims numbered nearly 500–540 military and police officials and up to 230 civilians.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina received technical support and military aid from the United States government during the Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, and Reagan administrations.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The exact chronology of the repression is still debated, yet the roots of the long political war may have started in 1969 when trade unionists were targeted for assassination by Peronist and Marxist paramilitaries.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Individual cases of state-sponsored terrorism against Peronism and the left can be traced back even further to the Bombing of Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Onganía shut down Congress, banned all political parties, and dismantled student and worker unions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 1969, popular discontent led to two massive protests: the *Cordobazo* and the *Rosariazo*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The terrorist guerrilla organisation Montoneros kidnapped and executed Aramburu.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The newly chosen head of government, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse, seeking to ease the growing political pressure, allowed Héctor José Cámpora to become the Peronist candidate instead of Perón.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Cámpora won the March 1973 election, issued pardons for condemned guerrilla members, and then secured Perón's return from his exile in Spain.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] On the day Perón returned to Argentina, the clash between Peronist internal factions—right-wing union leaders and left-wing youth from the Montoneros—resulted in the Ezeiza Massacre.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Overwhelmed by political violence, Cámpora resigned and Perón won the following September 1973 election with his third wife Isabel as vice-president.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He expelled Montoneros from the party and they became once again a clandestine organisation.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] José López Rega organised the Argentine Anticommunist Alliance (AAA) to fight against them and the People's Revolutionary Army (ERP).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Perón died in July 1974 and was succeeded by his wife, who signed a secret decree empowering the military and the police to "annihilate" the left-wing subversion, stopping ERP's attempt to start a rural insurgence in Tucumán province.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón was ousted one year later by a junta of the combined armed forces, led by army general Jorge Rafael Videla.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] They initiated the National Reorganization Process, often shortened to *Proceso*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The *Proceso* shut down Congress, removed the judges on the Supreme Court, banned political parties and unions, and resorted to employing the forced disappearance of suspected guerrilla members including individuals suspected of being associated with the left-wing.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] By the end of 1976, the Montoneros had lost nearly 2,000 members and by 1977, the ERP was completely subdued.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Nevertheless, the severely weakened Montoneros launched a counterattack in 1979, which was quickly put down, effectively ending the guerrilla threat and securing the junta's position in power.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In March 1982, an Argentine force took control of the British territory of South Georgia and, on 2 April, Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The United Kingdom dispatched a task force to regain possession.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina surrendered on 14 June and its forces were taken home.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Street riots in Buenos Aires followed the humiliating defeat and the military leadership stood down.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Reynaldo Bignone replaced Galtieri and began to organise the transition to democratic governance.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The worsening economic crisis and hyperinflation reduced his popular support and the Peronist Carlos Menem won the 1989 election.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Soon after, riots forced Alfonsín to an early resignation.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Menem embraced and enacted neoliberal policies: a fixed exchange rate, business deregulation, privatisations, and the dismantling of protectionist barriers normalised the economy in the short term.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He pardoned the officers who had been sentenced during Alfonsín's government.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The 1994 Constitutional Amendment allowed Menem to be elected for a second term.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] With the economy beginning to decline in 1995, and with increasing unemployment and recession, the UCR, led by Fernando de la Rúa, returned to the presidency in the 1999 elections.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] De la Rúa left Menem's economic plan in effect despite the worsening crisis, which led to growing social discontent.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Massive capital flight from the country was responded to with a freezing of bank accounts, generating further turmoil.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The December 2001 riots forced him to resign.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Congress appointed Eduardo Duhalde as acting president, who revoked the fixed exchange rate established by Menem, causing many working- and middle-class Argentines to lose a significant portion of their savings.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] By late 2002, the economic crisis began to recede, but the assassination of two *piqueteros* by the police caused political unrest, prompting Duhalde to move elections forward.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Néstor Kirchner was elected as the new president.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Boosting the neo-Keynesian economic policies laid by Duhalde, Kirchner ended the economic crisis attaining significant fiscal and trade surpluses, and rapid GDP growth.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He did not run for reelection, promoting instead the candidacy of his wife, senator Cristina Kirchner who won the 2007 and 2011 elections.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] During Kirchner's presidency she promoted foreign relations with countries such as Venezuela, Iran, and Cuba, whilst US and UK relations were increasingly strained.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Despite increased renewable energy production and subsidies during her tenure, the overall economy had been sluggish since 2011.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] On 22 November 2015, after a tie in the first round of presidential elections on 25 October, centre-right coalition candidate Mauricio Macri won the first ballotage in Argentina's history, beating Front for Victory candidate Daniel Scioli and becoming president-elect.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Macri was the first democratically elected non-peronist president since 1916 that managed to complete his term in office without being overthrown.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He took office on 10 December 2015 and inherited an economy with a high inflation rate and in a poor shape.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In April 2016, the Macri government introduced neoliberal austerity measures intended to tackle inflation and overblown public deficits.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Under Macri's administration, economic recovery remained elusive with GDP shrinking 3.4%, inflation totalling 240%, billions of US dollars issued in sovereign debt, and mass poverty increasing by the end of his term.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] He ran for reelection in 2019 but lost by nearly eight percentage points to Alberto Fernández, the Justicialist Party candidate.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Fernández and vice president Cristina Kirchner took office in December 2019, just months before the COVID-19 pandemic hit Argentina and among accusations of corruption, bribery and misuse of public funds during Néstor and Cristina Kirchner's presidencies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In November 2021, the centre-left coalition of Argentina's ruling Peronist party, Frente de Todos (Front for Everyone), lost its majority in Congress, for the first time in almost 40 years, in midterm legislative elections.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The election victory of the centre-right coalition, Juntos por el Cambio (Together for Change) limited Fernández' power during his final two years in office.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Losing control of the Senate made it difficult for him to make key appointments, including to the judiciary.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] It also forced him to negotiate with the opposition on every initiative sent to the legislature.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In April 2023, Fernández announced that he would not seek reelection in the next presidential election.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The November 2023 election run-off ended in a win for libertarian outsider Javier Milei with 55.7% of the vote against 44.4% to ruling coalition candidate Sergio Massa.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Milei's presidency began on 10 December 2023.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In October 2025, President Javier Milei's party, La Libertad Avanza, won a landslide victory in midterm elections, making it easier for Milei to push ahead with his programme of radical spending cuts and free-market reforms.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Its coastal border over the Río de la Plata and South Atlantic Ocean is 5,117 km (3,180 mi) long.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina's highest point is Aconcagua in the Mendoza province (6,959 m (22,831 ft) above sea level), also the highest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The lowest point is Laguna del Carbón in the *San Julián Great Depression* Santa Cruz province (−105 m (−344 ft) below sea level, also the lowest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres, and the seventh lowest point on Earth).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The maximum north–south distance is 3,694 km (2,295 mi), while the maximum east–west one is 1,423 km (884 mi).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Some of the major rivers are the Paraná, Uruguay—which join to form the Río de la Plata, Paraguay, Salado, Negro, Santa Cruz, Pilcomayo, Bermejo and Colorado.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] These rivers are discharged into the Argentine Sea, the shallow area of the Atlantic Ocean over the Patagonian Shelf, an unusually wide continental platform.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Its waters are influenced by two major ocean currents: the warm Brazil Current and the cold Falklands Current.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina is one of the most biodiverse countries in the world hosting one of the greatest ecosystem varieties in the world: 15 continental zones, 2 marine zones, and the Antarctic region are all represented in its territory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In Argentina forest cover is around 10% of the total land area, equivalent to 28,573,000 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 35,204,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 27,137,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,436,000 hectares (ha).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 7% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 4% private ownership and 96% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The original pampa had virtually no trees; some imported species such as the American sycamore or eucalyptus are present along roads or in towns and country estates (*estancias*).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The only tree-like plant native to the pampa is the evergreen Ombú.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The surface soils of the pampa are a deep black colour, primarily mollisols, known commonly as *humus*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] This makes the region one of the most agriculturally productive on Earth; however, this is also responsible for decimating much of the original ecosystem, to make way for commercial agriculture.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The western pampas receive less rainfall, this *dry pampa* is a plain of short grasses or steppe.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The National Parks of Argentina make up a network of 35 national parks in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The parks cover a very varied set of terrains and biotopes, from Baritú National Park on the northern border with Bolivia to Tierra del Fuego National Park in the far south of the continent.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Administración de Parques Nacionales (National Parks Administration) is the agency that preserves and manages these national parks along with Natural monuments and National Reserves within the country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Argentina had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 7.21/10, ranking it 47th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] In general, Argentina has four main climate types: warm humid subtropical, moderate humid subtropical, arid, and cold, all determined by the expanse across latitude, range in altitude, and relief features.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Although the most populated areas are generally temperate, Argentina has an exceptional amount of climate diversity, ranging from subtropical in the north to polar in the far south.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Consequently, there is a wide variety of biomes in the country, including Subtropical rainforests, semi-arid and arid regions, temperate plains in the Pampas, and cold subantarctic in the south.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The average annual precipitation ranges from 150 millimetres (6 in) in the driest parts of Patagonia to over 2,000 millimetres (79 in) in the westernmost parts of Patagonia and the northeastern parts of the country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Mean annual temperatures range from 5 °C (41 °F) in the far south to 25 °C (77 °F) in the north.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Major wind currents include the cool Pampero Winds blowing on the flat plains of Patagonia and the Pampas; following the cold front, warm currents blow from the north in middle and late winter, creating mild conditions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Sudestada usually moderates cold temperatures but brings very heavy rains, rough seas and coastal flooding.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] It is most common in late autumn and winter along the central coast and in the Río de la Plata estuary.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The Zonda, a hot dry wind, affects Cuyo and the central Pampas.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] Climate change in Argentina is predicted to have significant effects on the living conditions in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The climate of Argentina is changing with regards to precipitation patterns and temperatures.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The highest increases in precipitation (from the period 1960–2010) have occurred in the eastern parts of the country.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p01] The increase in precipitation has led to more variability in precipitation from year to year in the northern parts of the country, with a higher risk of prolonged droughts, disfavouring agriculture in these regions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In the 20th century, Argentina experienced significant political turmoil and democratic reversals.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Between 1930 and 1976, the armed forces overthrew six governments in Argentina; and the country alternated periods of democracy (1912–1930, 1946–1955, and 1973–1976) with periods of restricted democracy and military rule.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Following a transition that began in 1983, full-scale democracy in Argentina was reestablished.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina's democracy endured through the 2001–02 crisis and to the present day; it is regarded as more robust than both its pre-1983 predecessors and other democracies in Latin America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Argentina performs in the mid-range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in freedom of religion, inclusive suffrage, and civic engagement.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Moreover, according to the V-Dem Democracy indices, Argentina in 2023 was the second most electoral democratic country in Latin America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federal constitutional republic and representative democracy.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The government is regulated by a system of checks and balances defined by the Constitution of Argentina, the country's supreme legal document.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The seat of government is the city of Buenos Aires, as designated by Congress.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Suffrage is universal, equal, secret and mandatory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The federal government is composed of three branches.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Legislative branch consists of the bicameral Congress, made up of the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Congress makes federal law, declares war, approves treaties and has the power of the purse and of impeachment, by which it can remove sitting members of the government.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people and has 257 voting members elected to a four-year term.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Seats are apportioned among the provinces by population every tenth year.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] As of 2014 ten provinces have just five deputies while the Buenos Aires Province, being the most populous one, has 70.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Senators represents the provinces, and has 72 members elected at-large to six-year terms, with each province having three seats; one-third of Senate seats are up for election every other year.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] At least one-third of the candidates presented by the parties must be women.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In the Executive branch, the President is the commander-in-chief of the military, can veto legislative bills before they become law—subject to Congressional override—and appoints the members of the Cabinet and other officers, who administer and enforce federal laws and policies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The President is elected directly by the vote of the people, serves a four-year term and may be elected to office no more than twice in a row.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Judicial branch includes the Supreme Court and lower federal courts interpret laws and overturn those they find unconstitutional.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Judicial is independent of the Executive and the Legislative.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Supreme Court has seven members appointed by the President—subject to Senate approval—who serve for life.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The lower courts' judges are proposed by the Council of Magistracy (a secretariat composed of representatives of judges, lawyers, researchers, the Executive and the Legislative), and appointed by the president on Senate approval.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federation of twenty-three provinces and one autonomous city, Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Provinces are divided for administration purposes into departments and municipalities, except for Buenos Aires Province, which is divided into partidos.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The City of Buenos Aires is divided into communes.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Provinces hold all the power that they chose not to delegate to the federal government; they must be representative republics and must not contradict the Constitution.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Beyond this they are fully autonomous: they enact their own constitutions, freely organise their local governments, and own and manage their natural and financial resources.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Some provinces have bicameral legislatures, while others have unicameral ones.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] La Pampa and Chaco became provinces in 1951.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Misiones did so in 1953, and Formosa, Neuquén, Río Negro, Chubut and Santa Cruz, in 1955.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The last national territory, Tierra del Fuego, became the Tierra del Fuego, Antártida e Islas del Atlántico Sur Province in 1990.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] It has three components, although two are nominal because they are not under Argentine sovereignty.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Foreign policy is handled by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, International Trade and Worship, which answers to the President.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The country is one of the G-15 and G-20 major economies of the world, and a founding member of the UN, WBG, WTO and OAS.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2012 Argentina was elected again to a two-year non-permanent position on the United Nations Security Council and is participating in major peacekeeping operations in Haiti, Cyprus, Western Sahara and the Middle East.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is described as a middle power.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] A prominent Latin American and Southern Cone regional power, Argentina cofounded OEI and CELAC.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] It is also a founding member of the Mercosur block, having Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Venezuela as partners.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Since 2002 the country has emphasised its key role in Latin American integration, and the block—which has some supranational legislative functions—is its first international priority.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina claims 965,597 km2 (372,819 sq mi) in Antarctica, where it has the world's oldest continuous state presence, since 1904.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] This overlaps claims by Chile and the United Kingdom, though all such claims fall under the provisions of the 1961 Antarctic Treaty, of which Argentina is a founding signatory and permanent consulting member, with the Antarctic Treaty Secretariat being based in Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina disputes sovereignty over the British possessions of the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a party to the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a major non-NATO ally since 1998 and an OECD candidate country since January 2022.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Ruled and monitored by Congress through the Houses' Defence Committees, it is organised on the essential principle of legitimate self-defence: the repelling of any external military aggression in order to guarantee freedom of the people, national sovereignty, and territorial integrity.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Its secondary missions include committing to multinational operations within the framework of the United Nations, participating in internal support missions, assisting friendly countries, and establishing a sub-regional defence system.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Military service is voluntary, with enlistment age between 18 and 24 years old and no conscription.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina's defence has historically been one of the best equipped in the region, even managing its own weapon research facilities, shipyards, ordnance, tank and plane factories.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] However, real military expenditures declined steadily after the defeat in the Falklands/Malvinas War and the defence budget in 2011 was only about 0.74% of GDP, a historical minimum, below the Latin American average.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Within the defence budget itself, funding for training and even basic maintenance has been significantly cut, a factor contributing to the accidental loss of the Argentine submarine San Juan in 2017.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The result has been a steady erosion of Argentine military capabilities, with some arguing that Argentina had, by the end of the 2010s, ceased to be a capable military power.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Interior Security System is jointly administered by the federal and subscribing provincial governments.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] At the federal level it is coordinated by the Interior, Security and Justice ministries, and monitored by Congress.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] It is enforced by the Federal Police; the Prefecture, which fulfills coast guard duties; the Gendarmerie, which serves border guard tasks; and the Airport Security Police.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] At the provincial level it is coordinated by the respective internal security ministries and enforced by local police agencies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is the only Latin American country to maintain troops in Kosovo during SFOR (and later EUFOR) operations where combat engineers of the Argentine Armed Forces are embedded in an Italian brigade.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2007, an Argentine contingent including helicopters, boats and water purification plants was sent to help Bolivia against their worst floods in decades.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2010 the Armed Forces were also involved in Haiti and Chile humanitarian responses after their respective earthquakes.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Benefiting from rich natural resources, a highly literate population, a diversified industrial base, and an export-oriented agricultural sector, Argentina's economy is Latin America's third-largest, and the second-largest in South America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 1913, Argentina was one of the wealthiest countries in the world by GDP per capita.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] It has a "very high" rating on the Human Development Index and ranks 66th by nominal GDP per capita, with a considerable internal market size and a growing share of the high-tech sector.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] As a middle emerging economy and one of the world's top developing nations, it is a member of the G-20 major economies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] It is the largest producer in South America of wheat, sunflower seed, barley, lemon and pear.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In wine, Argentina is usually among the ten largest producers in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a traditional meat exporter, having been, in 2019, the 4th world producer of beef, with a production of 3 million tons (only behind US, Brazil and China), the 4th world producer of honey, and the 10th world producer of wool, in addition to other relevant productions.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The mining industry of Argentina is less prominent compared to other countries but stands out as the fourth-largest producer of lithium, the 11th-largest of silver and 17th-largest of gold worldwide.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina excels in natural gas production, being the largest producer in South America and the 18th-largest globally.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina produces an average of 500,000 barrels/day of petroleum, despite the under-utilisation of the Vaca Muerta field due to technical and financial limitations in resource extraction.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2012, manufacturing accounted for 20.3% of GDP—the largest sector in Argentina's economy.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Well-integrated into Argentine agriculture, half of the industrial exports have rural origin.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] With a 6.5% production growth rate in 2011, the diversified manufacturing sector rests on a steadily growing network of industrial parks, 314 in 2013.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina has since long been one of the top five wine-producing countries in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks 85th out of 180 countries in the Transparency International's 2017 Corruption Perceptions Index, an improvement of 22 positions over its 2014 rankings.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina settled its long-standing debt default crisis in 2016 with the so-called vulture funds after the election of Mauricio Macri, allowing Argentina to enter capital markets for the first time in a decade.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The government of Argentina defaulted in May 2020 by failing to pay a $500 million bill by its due date to its creditors.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Negotiations for the restructuring of $66 billion of its debt continue.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] High inflation—a weakness of the Argentine economy for decades—has become a trouble once again, recently peaking at 220% in 2024.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Approximately 43% of the Argentina's population lived below the poverty line in 2023.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] To deter it and support the peso, the government imposed foreign currency control.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Income distribution, having improved since 2002, is classified as "medium", although it is still considerably unequal.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] On 10 December 2023, Javier Milei was sworn in as president.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] He pursued deregulation policies to alleviate the national economic crisis.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In January 2024, Argentina's poverty rate reached 57.4%, the highest poverty rate in the country since 2004.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] By the second semester of 2024, however, poverty levels had fallen sharply to 38%, the lowest since 2022.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In November 2024, Argentina's monthly inflation rate slowed to 2.4%, the lowest in over four years.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Annual inflation was expected to end 2024 closer to 100%.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Favourable results and normalisation in Argentina's economy are expected to continue in 2025.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The annual inflation rate is expected to be below 30% in 2025.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Economic activity has also begun to recover after the severe recession at the beginning of 2024.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The economy is expected to expand by more than 4% in 2025.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina had 5.57 million visitors in 2013, the top international tourist destination in South America, and the second in Latin America after Mexico.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Revenues from international tourists reached US$4.41 billion in 2013, down from US$4.89 billion in 2012.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina's capital city, Buenos Aires, is the most visited city in South America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] There are 30 National Parks of Argentina including many World Heritage Sites.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2004, Buenos Aires, all provincial capitals except Ushuaia, and all medium-sized towns were interconnected by 69,412 km (43,131 mi) of paved roads, out of a road network of 231,374 km (143,769 mi).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2021, Argentina had about 2,800 km (1,740 mi) of dual carriageways, most leaving the capital Buenos Aires, linking it with cities such as Rosario and Córdoba, Santa Fe, Mar del Plata and Paso de los Libres (bordering Brazil).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] There are also dual carriageways leaving from Mendoza towards the capital, and between Córdoba and Santa Fé, among other locations.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Nevertheless, this road infrastructure is still inadequate and cannot handle the sharply growing demand caused by deterioration of the railway system.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina has the largest railway system in Latin America, with 36,966 km (22,970 mi) of operating lines in 2008, out of a network of almost 48,000 km (29,826 mi).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] This system links all 23 provinces, plus Buenos Aires City, and connects with all neighbouring countries.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] There are four incompatible gauges in use; this forces virtually all interregional freight traffic to pass through Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The system has been in decline since the 1940s: regularly running up large budgetary deficits.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] By 1991, it was transporting 1,400 times less goods than it did in 1973.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] However, in recent years the system has experienced a greater degree of investment from the state, in both commuter rail lines and long-distance lines, renewing rolling stock and infrastructure.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In April 2015, by overwhelming majority the Argentine Senate passed a law which recreated Ferrocarriles Argentinos, effectively renationalising the country's railways, a move which saw support from all major political parties on both sides of the political spectrum.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2012, there were about 11,000 km (6,835 mi) of waterways, mostly comprising the La Plata, Paraná, Paraguay and Uruguay rivers, with Buenos Aires, Zárate, Campana, Rosario, San Lorenzo, Santa Fe, Barranqueras and San Nicolas de los Arroyos as the main fluvial ports.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Some of the largest sea ports are La Plata–Ensenada, Bahía Blanca, Mar del Plata, Quequén–Necochea, Comodoro Rivadavia, Puerto Deseado, Puerto Madryn, Ushuaia and San Antonio Oeste.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Buenos Aires has historically been the most important port.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Since the 1990s the Up-River port region has become dominant: stretching along 67 km (42 mi) of the Paraná river shore in Santa Fe province, it includes 17 ports and in 2013 accounted for 50% of all exports.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 161 airports with paved runways out of more than a thousand.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Ezeiza International Airport, about 35 km (22 mi) from downtown Buenos Aires, is the largest in Argentina, followed by Cataratas del Iguazú in Misiones, and El Plumerillo in Mendoza.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Aeroparque, in the city of Buenos Aires, is the most important domestic airport.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2020, more than 60% of Argentina's electricity came from non-renewable sources such as natural gas, oil and coal.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] 27% came from hydropower, 7.3% from wind and solar energy and 4.4% from nuclear energy.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] At the end of 2021 Argentina was the 21st country in the world in terms of installed hydroelectric power (11.3 GW), the 26th country in the world in terms of installed wind energy (3.2 GW) and the 43rd country in the world in terms of installed solar energy (1.0 GW).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The wind potential of the Patagonia region is considered gigantic, with estimates that the area could provide enough electricity to sustain the consumption of a country like Brazil alone.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] However, Argentina has faced infrastructural challenges in transferring electricity from wind-rich rural areas to its population hubs.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 1974, Argentina was the first country in Latin America to put a commercial nuclear power plant online, Atucha I.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Although the Argentine-built parts for that station amounted to 10% of the total, the nuclear fuel it uses are from Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Later nuclear power stations employed a higher percentage of Argentine-built components.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Embalse, finished in 1983, used 30% and the 2011 Atucha II reactor used 40%.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentines have received three Nobel Prizes in the Sciences.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Bernardo Houssay, the first Latin American recipient, discovered the role of pituitary hormones in regulating glucose in animals, and shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1947.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Luis Leloir discovered how organisms store energy converting glucose into glycogen and the compounds which are fundamental in metabolising carbohydrates, receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1970.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] César Milstein did extensive research in antibodies, sharing the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentine research has led to treatments for heart diseases and several forms of cancer.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Domingo Liotta designed and developed the first artificial heart that was successfully implanted in a human being in 1969.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] René Favaloro developed the techniques and performed the world's first coronary bypass surgery.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina was the first country in Latin America to design and build a research reactor with homegrown technology, the RA-1 Enrico Fermi.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] This reliance on the development of its own nuclear-related technologies, instead of buying them abroad, was a constant of Argentina's nuclear programme conducted by the civilian National Atomic Energy Commission (CNEA).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Nuclear facilities with Argentine technology have been built in Peru, Algeria, Australia and Egypt.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 1983, Argentina admitted having the capability of producing weapon-grade uranium, a major step needed to assemble nuclear weapons.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Since then, Argentina has pledged to use nuclear power only for peaceful purposes.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] As a member of the Board of Governors of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Argentina supports nuclear non-proliferation efforts and is committed to global nuclear security.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentine scientists are still on the cutting edge in fields such as nanotechnology, physics, computer sciences, molecular biology, oncology, ecology and cardiology.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Juan Maldacena, an Argentine-American scientist, is a leading figure in string theory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Space research has become increasingly active in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentine-built satellites include LUSAT-1 (1990), Víctor-1 (1996), PEHUENSAT-1 (2007), and those developed by CONAE, the Argentine space agency, of the SAC series.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina has its own satellite programme, nuclear power station designs (4th generation) and public nuclear energy company INVAP, which provides several countries with nuclear reactors.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Established in 1991, the CONAE has since launched two satellites successfully.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In June 2009, CONAE secured an agreement with the European Space Agency for the installation of a 35-m diametre antenna and other mission support facilities at the Pierre Auger Observatory, the world's foremost cosmic ray observatory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The facility will contribute to numerous ESA space probes, as well as CONAE's own, domestic research projects.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Chosen from 20 potential sites and one of only three such ESA installations in the world, the new antenna will create a triangulation which will allow the ESA to ensure mission coverage around the clock.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina was ranked 76th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, and was ranked 77th in 2025.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Latin American Mammalogy Network (Red Latinoamericana de Mastozoología, or RELAM) was created during the 2009 IMC Congress, cofounded by SAREM and the Asociación Boliviana de Investigadores en Mamíferos (Bolivian Association of Mammal Researchers, ABIMA).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The electronic scientific journal *Therya*, conceived during IMC 10, began publication by the Mexican Association of Mammalogy (AMMAC), in 2010.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Lidicker Jr., who presided over IMC 10, was the editor.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The population in 2024 is estimated to have increased to 47,067,441 inhabitants.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks third in South America in total population, fourth in Latin America and 33rd globally.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Its population density of 15 persons per square kilometre of land area is well below the world average of 50 persons.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The population growth rate in 2010 was an estimated 1.03% annually, with a birth rate of 17.7 live births per 1,000 inhabitants and a mortality rate of 7.4 deaths per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Since 2010, the crude net migration rate has ranged from below zero to up to four immigrants per 1,000 inhabitants per year.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is in the midst of a demographic transition to an older and slower-growing population.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The proportion of people under 15 is 25.6%, a little below the world average of 28%, and the proportion of people 65 and older is relatively high at 10.8%.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In Latin America, this is second only to Uruguay and well above the world average, which is currently 7%.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina has a comparatively low infant mortality rate.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina's 2010 birth rate of 2.3 children per woman was considerably below the high of 7.0 children born per woman in 1895, though still nearly twice as high as in Spain or Italy, which are culturally and demographically similar.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2015, the median age was 31.9 years and life expectancy at birth was 77.14 years.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Attitudes towards LGBT people are generally positive within Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2010, Argentina became the first country in Latin America, the second in the Americas, and the tenth worldwide to legalise same-sex marriage.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is highly urbanised, with 92% of its population living in cities: the ten largest metropolitan areas account for half of the population.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] About 3 million people live in the city of Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Greater Buenos Aires metropolitan area has around 13 million, making it one of the largest urban areas in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The metropolitan areas of Córdoba and Rosario have around 1.3 million inhabitants each.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Mendoza, San Miguel de Tucumán, La Plata, Mar del Plata, Salta and Santa Fe have at least half a million people each.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The population is unequally distributed: about 60% live in the Pampas region (21% of the total area), including 15 million people in Buenos Aires province.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The provinces of Córdoba and Santa Fe, and the city of Buenos Aires have 3 million each.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Seven other provinces have over one million people each: Mendoza, Tucumán, Entre Ríos, Salta, Chaco, Corrientes and Misiones.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] With 64.3 inhabitants per square kilometre (167/sq mi), Tucumán is the only Argentine province more densely populated than the world average.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] By contrast, the southern province of Santa Cruz has around 1.1/km2 (2.8/sq mi).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is considered a country of immigrants.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentines usually refer to the country as a *crisol de razas* (crucible of races, or melting pot).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] A 2010 study conducted on 218 individuals by the Argentine geneticist Daniel Corach established that the average genetic ancestry of Argentines is 79% European (mainly Italian and Spanish), 18% indigenous and 4.3% African.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] 63.6% of the tested group had at least one ancestor who was Indigenous.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The majority of Argentines descend from multiple European ethnic groups, primarily of Italian and Spanish descent, with over 25 million Argentines, almost 60% of the population, having some partial Italian origins.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to a notable Asian population, the majority of whom are descended from either West Asians, namely Lebanese and Syrians, or East Asians, such as the Chinese, Koreans, and the Japanese.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The latter of whom number around 180,000 individuals.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The total number of Arab Argentines (most of whom are of Lebanese or Syrian origin) is estimated to be 1.3 to 3.5 million.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Many immigrated from Asian countries to Argentina during the latter half of 19th century, and the first half of the 20th century.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Most Arab Argentines belong to the Catholic Church, including both the Latin Church and the Eastern Catholic Churches, or the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2018, there were 180,000 Alawites in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Since the 1970s, immigration has mostly been coming from Bolivia, Paraguay and Peru, with smaller numbers from the Dominican Republic, Ecuador and Romania.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2008, the Argentine government estimated that 750,000 inhabitants lack official documents and has launched a programme to encourage illegal immigrants to declare their status in return for two-year residence visas—so far over 670,000 applications have been processed under the programme.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] As of July 2023, more than 18,500 Russians have come to Argentina after the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The *de facto* official language is Spanish, spoken by almost all Argentines.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is the largest Spanish-speaking society that universally employs *voseo*, the use of the pronoun *vos* instead of *tú* ("you"), which imposes the use of alternative verb forms as well.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Owing to the extensive Argentine geography, Spanish has a strong variation among regions, although the prevalent dialect is *Rioplatense*, primarily spoken in the Pampean and Patagonian regions and accented similarly to the Neapolitan language.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Italian and other European immigrants influenced *Lunfardo*—the regional slang—permeating the vernacular vocabulary of other Latin American countries as well.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Christianity is the largest religion in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Constitution guarantees freedom of religion.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Although it enforces neither an official nor a state faith, it gives Roman Catholicism a preferential status.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2008, Argentines were 76.5% Catholic, 11.3% Agnostics and Atheists, 9% Evangelical Protestants, 1.2% Jehovah's Witnesses, and 0.9% Mormons, while 1.2% followed other religions, including Islam, Judaism and Buddhism.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] These figures appear to have changed quite significantly in recent years: in 2017, Catholics were 66% of the population, indicating a drop of 10.5% in nine years, and the nonreligious in the country standing at 21% of the population, indicating an almost doubling over the same period.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2024, Catholics were 63% of the population.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] 20% of Argentines are irreligious, 9% are Protestants, and 8% follow another religion or didn't answer.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to both one of the largest Muslim and largest Jewish communities in Latin America, the latter being the seventh most populous in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentina is a member of the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Argentines show high individualisation and deinstitutionalisation of religious beliefs.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] 23.8% claim to always attend religious services; 49.1% seldom do and 26.8% never do.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] On 13 March 2013, Argentine Jorge Mario Bergoglio, the Cardinal Archbishop of Buenos Aires, was elected Bishop of Rome and Supreme Pontiff of the Catholic Church.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] He took the name "Francis", and he became the first Pope from either the Americas or from the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] He is the first Pope born outside of Europe since the election of Pope Gregory III, who was Syrian, in 741.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Argentine education system consists of four levels.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] An initial level for children between 45 days to 5 years old, with the last two years being compulsory.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] An elementary or lower school mandatory level lasting 6 or 7 years.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] A secondary or high school mandatory level lasts 5 or 6 years.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2010, 38.5% of people over age 20 had completed secondary school.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Higher education is divided into tertiary, university and post-graduate sub-levels.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 47 national public universities across the country, and 46 private ones.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In 2010, 7.1% of people over age 20 had graduated from university.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The public universities of Buenos Aires, Córdoba, La Plata, Rosario, and the National Technological University are some of the most important.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The Argentine state guarantees universal, secular and free-of-charge public education for all levels.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Responsibility for educational supervision is organised at the federal and individual provincial states.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] In the last decades the role of the private sector has grown across all educational stages.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Healthcare is provided through a combination of employer and labour union-sponsored plans (*Obras Sociales*), government insurance plans, public hospitals and clinics and through private health insurance plans.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Healthcare cooperatives number over 300 (of which 200 are related to labour unions) and provide healthcare for half the population; the national INSSJP (popularly known as PAMI) covers nearly all of the five million senior citizens.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] There are more than 153,000 hospital beds, 121,000 physicians and 37,000 dentists, ratios comparable to developed nations.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Causes related to senility led to many of the rest.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Infant deaths have fallen from 19% of all deaths in 1953 to 3% in 2005.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] The availability of healthcare has also reduced infant mortality from 70 per 1000 live births in 1948 to 12.1 in 2009 and raised life expectancy at birth from 60 years to 76.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p02] Though these figures compare favourably with global averages, they fall short of levels in developed nations and in 2006, Argentina ranked fourth in Latin America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentina is a multicultural country with significant European influences.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Modern Argentine culture has been largely influenced by Italian, Spanish and other European immigration from France, Russia, United Kingdom, among others.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Its cities are largely characterised by both the prevalence of people of European descent, and of conscious imitation of American and European styles in fashion, architecture and design.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The other big influence is the gauchos and their traditional country lifestyle of self-reliance.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Indigenous American traditions have been absorbed into the general cultural milieu.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The Modernist movement advanced into the 20th century including exponents such as Leopoldo Lugones and poet Alfonsina Storni; it was followed by Vanguardism, with Ricardo Güiraldes's *Don Segundo Sombra* as an important reference.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Jorge Luis Borges, Argentina's most acclaimed writer and one of the foremost figures in the history of literature, found new ways of looking at the modern world in metaphor and philosophical debate and his influence has extended to authors all over the globe.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Short stories such as *Ficciones* and *The Aleph* are among his most famous works.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] He was a friend and collaborator of Adolfo Bioy Casares, who wrote one of the most praised science fiction novels, *The Invention of Morel*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Julio Cortázar, one of the leading members of the Latin American Boom and a major name in 20th century literature, influenced an entire generation of writers in the Americas and Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Tango, a *Rioplatense* musical genre with European and African influences, is one of Argentina's international cultural symbols.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The golden age of tango, from 1930 to the mid-1950s, mirrored that of jazz and swing in the United States, featuring large orchestras such as those of Osvaldo Pugliese, Aníbal Troilo, Francisco Canaro, Julio de Caro and Juan d'Arienzo.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] After 1955, virtuoso Astor Piazzolla popularised *Nuevo tango*, a subtler and more intellectual trend for the genre.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Tango enjoys worldwide popularity nowadays with groups such as Gotan Project, Bajofondo and Tanghetto.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] A national Argentine folk style emerged in the 1930s from dozens of regional musical genres and went on to influence the entirety of Latin American music.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Some of its interpreters, such as Atahualpa Yupanqui and Mercedes Sosa, achieved worldwide acclaim.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The romantic ballad genre included singers of international fame such as Sandro de América.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Tenor saxophonist Leandro "Gato" Barbieri and composer and big band conductor Lalo Schifrin are among the most internationally successful Argentine jazz musicians.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentine rock developed as a distinct musical style in the mid-1960s, when Buenos Aires and Rosario became cradles of aspiring musicians.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] A dance and a musical genre popular at present is Cachengue, a subgenre of Argentine cumbia and reggaeton spreading in popularity in nearby countries such as Uruguay, Chile, Paraguay, and Bolivia.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Buenos Aires is one of the great theatre capitals of the world, with a scene of international caliber centred on Corrientes Avenue, "the street that never sleeps", sometimes referred to as the Broadway of Buenos Aires.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Teatro Colón is a global landmark for opera and classical performances; its acoustics are considered among the world's top five.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The Argentine film industry has historically been one of the three most developed in Latin American cinema, along with those produced in Mexico and Brazil.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] By the early 1930s, it was Latin America's leading film producer, a place it kept until the early 1950s.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The world's first animated feature films were made and released in Argentina, by cartoonist Quirino Cristiani, in 1917 and 1918.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentine films have achieved worldwide recognition: Argentina has won two Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film, for *The Official Story* (1985) and *The Secret in Their Eyes* (2009).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentine composers Luis Enrique Bacalov and Gustavo Santaolalla have been honoured with Academy Awards for Best Original Score, and Armando Bó and Nicolás Giacobone shared in the Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay for 2014.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The Argentine French actress Bérénice Bejo received a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress in 2011 and won the César Award for Best Actress and won the Best Actress award in the Cannes Film Festival for her role in the film *The Past*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentina has won seventeen Goya Awards for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film, being by far the most awarded country in Latin America with twenty-four nominations.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Many other Argentine films have been acclaimed by international critique.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] In 2013, about 100 full-length motion pictures were being created annually.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] In 1946, Gyula Košice and others created The Madí Movement in Argentina, which then spread to Europe and the United States, where it had a significant impact.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Tomás Maldonado was one of the main theorists of the Ulm Model of design education, still highly influential globally.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Other Argentine artists of worldwide fame include Adolfo Bellocq, whose lithographs have been influential since the 1920s, and Benito Quinquela Martín, the quintessential port painter, inspired by the immigrant-bound La Boca neighbourhood.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Internationally laureate sculptors Erminio Blotta, Lola Mora and Rogelio Yrurtia authored many of the classical evocative monuments of the Argentine cityscape.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The colonisation brought the Spanish Baroque architecture, which can still be appreciated in its simpler *Rioplatense* style in the reduction of San Ignacio Miní, the Cathedral of Córdoba, and the Cabildo of Luján.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Italian and French influences increased at the beginning of the 19th century with strong eclectic overtones that gave the local architecture a unique feeling.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The print media industry is highly developed in Argentina, with more than two hundred newspapers.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The major national ones include *Clarín* (centrist, Latin America's best-seller and the second most widely circulated in the Spanish-speaking world), *La Nación* (centre-right), *Página/12* (leftist), *La Voz del Interior* (centre).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentina began the world's first regular radio broadcasting on 27 August 1920, when Richard Wagner's *Parsifal* was aired by a team of medical students led by Enrique Telémaco Susini in Buenos Aires' Teatro Coliseo.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] In 2002, there were 260 AM and 1150 FM registered radio stations in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The Argentine television industry is large, diverse and popular across Latin America, with many productions and TV formats having been exported abroad.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Since 1999 Argentines have enjoyed the highest availability of cable and satellite television in Latin America.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] In 2014, 87.4% of Argentina's households had access, a rate similar to those in the United States, Canada and Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] As of early 2024, internet penetration in Argentina stood at 88.4% of the total population, and the ratio of cellular mobile connections to the total population was 135.3% (62.14 million active connections).
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Besides many of the pasta, sausage and dessert dishes common to continental Europe, Argentines enjoy a wide variety of Indigenous and Criollo creations, including *empanadas* (a small stuffed pastry), *locro* (a mixture of corn, beans, meat, bacon, onion, and gourd), *humita* and *mate*.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The country has the highest consumption of red meat in the world, traditionally prepared as *asado*, the Argentine barbecue.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] It is made with various types of meats, often including *chorizo*, sweetbread, chitterlings, and blood sausage.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentine wine, one of the world's finest, is an integral part of the local menu.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Malbec, Torrontés, Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah and Chardonnay are some of the most sought-after varieties.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Along with Brazil, Germany and France, the men's national team is the only one to have won each of the World Cup (in 1978, 1986 and 2022), Confederations Cup, and the Olympic gold.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] They have also won 16 Copas América, 7 Pan American Gold Medals and many other trophies.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Alfredo Di Stéfano, Diego Maradona and Lionel Messi are widely considered to be among the best players in the game's history.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The country's women's field hockey team *Las Leonas*, is one of the world's most successful with four Olympic medals, two World Cups, a World League and seven Champions Trophy.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Luciana Aymar is recognised as the best female player in the history of the sport, being the only player to have received the FIH Player of the Year Award eight times.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The men's national team is the only one in the FIBA Americas zone that has won the quintuplet crown: World Championship, Olympic Gold Medal, Diamond Ball, Americas Championship, and Pan American Gold Medal.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] It has also conquered 13 South American Championships, and many other tournaments.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Emanuel Ginóbili, Luis Scola, Andrés Nocioni, Fabricio Oberto, Pablo Prigioni, Carlos Delfino and Juan Ignacio Sánchez are a few of the country's most acclaimed players, all of them part of the NBA.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentina hosted the Basketball World Cup in 1950 and 1990.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Rugby is another popular sport in Argentina.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] As of 2017, the men's national team, known as 'Los Pumas' has competed at the Rugby World Cup each time it has been held, achieving their highest-ever result in 2007 when they came third.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Since 2012, the Los Pumas have competed against Australia, New Zealand & South Africa in The Rugby Championship, the premier international Rugby competition in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Since 2009 the secondary men's national team known as the 'Jaguares' has competed against the US, Canada, and Uruguay first teams in the Americas Rugby Championship, which Los Jaguares have won six out of eight times it has taken place.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Tennis has been quite popular among people of all ages.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Guillermo Vilas is the greatest Latin American player of the Open Era, while Gabriela Sabatini is the most accomplished Argentine female player of all time—having reached number 3 in the WTA ranking, are both inductees into the International Tennis Hall of Fame.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The national squad won the 2016 Davis Cup.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Argentina reigns undisputed in polo, having won more international championships than any other country and been seldom beaten since the 1930s.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The Argentine Polo Championship is the sport's most important international team trophy.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] The country is home to most of the world's top players, among them Adolfo Cambiaso, the best in Polo history.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Historically, Argentina has had a strong showing within auto racing.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Juan Manuel Fangio was a five-time Formula One world champion under four different teams, winning 102 of his 184 international races, and is widely ranked as the greatest driver of all time.
[src:fargo-trucks/argentina-p03] Other distinguished racers were Oscar Alfredo Gálvez, Juan Gálvez, José Froilán González and Carlos Reutemann.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia shares the landmass of Eurasia with Europe, and of Afro-Eurasia with both Europe and Africa.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] In general terms, it is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean, and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The border of Asia with Europe is a historical and cultural construct, as there is no clear physical and geographical separation between them.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] A commonly accepted division places Asia to the east of the Suez Canal separating it from Africa; and to the east of the Turkish straits, the Ural Mountains and Ural River, and to the south of the Caucasus Mountains and the Caspian and Black seas, separating it from Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Since the concept of Asia derives from the term for the eastern region from a European perspective, Asia is the remaining vast area of Eurasia minus Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Therefore, Asia is a region where various independent cultures coexist rather than sharing a single culture, and its boundary with Europe is somewhat arbitrary and has moved since its first conception in classical antiquity.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The division of Eurasia into two continents reflects East–West cultural differences, some of which vary on a spectrum.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] China and India traded places as the largest economies in the world from 1 to 1800 CE.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] China was a major economic power for much of recorded history, with the highest GDP per capita until 1500.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Silk Road became the main east–west trading route in the Asian hinterlands while the Straits of Malacca stood as a major sea route.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia has exhibited economic dynamism as well as robust population growth during the 20th century, but overall population growth has since fallen.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia was the birthplace of most of the world's mainstream religions including Islam, Judaism, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism, and many other religions.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia varies greatly across and within its regions with regard to ethnic groups, cultures, environments, economics, historical ties, and government systems.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The term "Asia" is believed to originate in the Bronze Age toponym *Assuwa* (Hittite: 𒀸𒋗𒉿, romanized: *aš-šu-wa*) which originally referred only to a portion of northwestern Anatolia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The term appears in Hittite records recounting how a confederation of Assuwan states including Troy unsuccessfully rebelled against the Hittite king Tudhaliya I around 1400 BCE.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Roughly contemporary Linear B documents contain the term *aswia* (Mycenaean Greek: 𐀀𐀯𐀹𐀊, romanized: *a-si-wi-ja*), seemingly in reference to captives from the same area.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Herodotus used the term in reference to Anatolia and the territory of the Achaemenid Empire, in contrast to Greece and Egypt.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] He reports that Greeks assumed that Asia was named after the wife of Prometheus, but that Lydians say it was named after *Asies*, son of Cotys, who passed the name on to a tribe at Sardis.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] In Greek mythology, "Asia" (Ἀσία or Ἀσίη) was the name of a "Nymph or Titan goddess of Lydia".
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Iliad (attributed by the ancient Greeks to Homer) mentions two Phrygians in the Trojan War named Asios (literally 'Asian'); and also a marsh or lowland containing a marsh in Lydia as ασιος.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The term was later adopted by the Romans, who used it in reference to the province of Asia, located in western Anatolia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] One of the first writers to use Asia as a name of the whole continent was Pliny.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The threefold division of the Old World into Africa, Asia, and Europe has been in use since the 6th century BCE, due to Greek geographers such as Anaximander and Hecataeus.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Anaximander placed the boundary between Asia and Europe along the Phasis River (now the Rioni) in Georgia of Caucasus (from its mouth by Poti on the Black Sea coast, through the Surami Pass and along the Kura River to the Caspian Sea), a convention still followed by Herodotus in the 5th century BCE.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] During the Hellenistic period, this convention was revised, and the boundary between Europe and Asia was now considered to be the Tanais (the modern Don River).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This is the convention used by Roman era authors such as Posidonius, Strabo and Ptolemy.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Europe was later redefined by European academics.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] In 1730, five years after the death of Peter the Great, Philip Johan von Strahlenberg published in Sweden a new atlas proposing the Ural Mountains as the border of Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Vasily Tatishchev announced that he had proposed the idea to von Strahlenberg.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The latter had suggested the Emba River as the southern part of this boundary.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Over the next century various proposals were made until the Ural River prevailed in the mid-19th century.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The border had been moved perforce from the Black Sea (the Romans' definition) to the Caspian Sea into which the Emba and Ural rivers project.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Between the Black Sea and the Caspian, the border is often placed along the crest of the Caucasus Mountains, although it is sometimes placed further north, on the Kuma–Manych Depression.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The boundary between Asia and Africa is the Suez Canal, the Gulf of Suez, the Red Sea, and the Bab-el-Mandeb.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This makes Egypt a transcontinental country, with the Sinai Peninsula in Asia and the remainder of the country in Africa.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Oceania is usually placed somewhere in the Indonesian Archipelago, specifically in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Wallace Line separates the Asian and Wallacea biogeographical realms, a transition zone of deep water straits between the Asian and Australian continental shelves.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Weber's Line split the region in two with regard to the balance of fauna between Asian origin or Australo-Papuan origin.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Wallacea's eastern boundary with Sahul is represented by the Lydekker's Line.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Maluku Islands (except the Aru Islands) are often considered to lie on the border of southeast Asia, with the Aru Islands and Western New Guinea, to the east of the Lydekker's Line, being wholly part of Oceania, as both lie on the Australian continental plate.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Culturally, the Wallacea region denoted the transition between Austronesian and Melanesian people, with varying degrees of intermixing between the two.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] In general, the further west and coastal a region is, the stronger the Austronesian influences, and the further east and inland a region is, the stronger the Melanesian influences.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The terms Southeast Asia and Oceania, devised in the 19th century, have had several vastly different geographic meanings since their inception.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The chief factor in determining which islands of the Indonesian Archipelago are Asian has been the location of the colonial possessions of the various empires there (not all European).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Bering Strait and Bering Sea separate the landmasses of Asia and North America, as well as forming the international boundary between Russia and the United States.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This national and continental boundary separates the Diomede Islands in the Bering Strait, with Big Diomede in Russia and Little Diomede in the United States.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are an island chain extending westward from the Alaskan Peninsula toward Russia's Komandorski Islands and Kamchatka Peninsula.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are sometimes associated with Oceania, owing to their status as remote Pacific islands, and their proximity to the Pacific Plate.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This is extremely rare however, due to their non-tropical biogeography, as well as their inhabitants, who have historically been related to the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Lawrence Island in the northern Bering Sea belongs to the US state of Alaska and may be associated with either continent but is almost always considered part of North America, as with the Rat Islands in the Aleutian chain.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] At their nearest points, Alaska and Russia are separated by only 4 kilometres (2.5 miles).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Geographical Asia is a cultural artifact of European conceptions of the world, beginning with the Ancient Greeks, being imposed onto other cultures, an imprecise concept causing endemic contention about what it means.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia does not exactly correspond to the cultural borders of its various types of constituents.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] From the time of Herodotus, a minority of geographers have rejected the three-continent system (Europe, Africa, Asia) on the grounds that there is no substantial physical separation between them.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] For example, Sir Barry Cunliffe, the emeritus professor of European archeology at Oxford, argues that Europe has been geographically and culturally merely "the western excrescence of the continent of Asia".
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Geographically, Asia is the major eastern constituent of the continent of Eurasia with Europe being a northwestern peninsula of the landmass.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia, Europe and Africa make up a single continuous landmass—Afro-Eurasia—and share a common continental shelf.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Almost all of Europe and a major part of Asia sit atop the Eurasian Plate, adjoined on the south by the Arabian and Indian Plate and with the easternmost part of Siberia (east of the Chersky Range) on the North American Plate.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] About 1.8 million years ago, *Homo erectus* left the African continent.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This species is believed to have lived in East and Southeast Asia from 1.8 million to 110,000 years ago.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Researchers believe that the modern human, or *Homo sapiens*, migrated about 60,000 years ago to South Asia along the Indian Ocean.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Modern humans interbred with an archaic human species called Denisovans in Southeast Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Before the arrival of modern humans, Flores was occupied by *Homo floresiensis*, a small archaic human.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Ancestors of East Eurasians split from Ancient West Eurasians about 46,000 years ago, migrating out of the hub in the Iranian Plateau.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The history of Asia can be seen as the distinct histories of several peripheral coastal regions: East Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, Central Asia, and West Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The coastal periphery was home to some of the world's earliest known civilisations, each of them developing around fertile river valleys.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The civilisations in Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley and the Yellow River shared many similarities.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] These civilisations may well have exchanged technologies and ideas such as mathematics and the wheel.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Other innovations, such as writing, seem to have been developed individually in each area.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Cities, states and empires developed in these lowlands.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The central steppe region had long been inhabited by horse-mounted nomads who could reach all areas of Asia from the steppes.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The earliest postulated expansion out of the steppe is that of the Indo-Europeans, who spread their languages into West Asia, South Asia, and the borders of China, where the Tocharians resided.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The northernmost part of Asia, including much of Siberia, was largely inaccessible to the steppe nomads, owing to the dense forests, climate and tundra.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] These areas remained very sparsely populated.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The center and the peripheries were mostly kept separated by mountains and deserts.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Caucasus and Himalaya mountains and the Karakum and Gobi deserts formed barriers that the steppe horsemen could cross only with difficulty.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] While the urban city dwellers were more advanced technologically and socially, in many cases they could do little in a military aspect to defend against the mounted hordes of the steppe.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] However, the lowlands did not have enough open grasslands to support a large equestrian force; for this and other reasons, the nomads who conquered states in China, India, and the Middle East often found themselves adapting to the local, more affluent societies.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Mongol Empire conquered a large part of Asia in the 13th century, an area extending from China to Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Before the Mongol invasion, Song dynasty reportedly had approximately 120 million citizens; the 1300 census which followed the invasion reported roughly 60 million people.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Black Death, one of the most devastating pandemics in human history, is thought to have originated in the arid plains of central Asia, where it then travelled along the Silk Road.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] European involvement in Asia became more significant from the Age of Discovery onward, with Iberian-sponsored sailors such as Christopher Columbus and Vasco da Gama paving the way for new routes from Atlantic Europe to Pacific Asia and the Indian Ocean respectively in the late 15th century.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Russian Empire also began to expand into northwestern Asia from the 17th century, and would eventually take control of all of Siberia and most of Central Asia by the end of the 19th century.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Among non-European empires, the Ottoman Empire controlled Anatolia, most of the Middle East, North Africa and the Balkans from the mid 16th century onward, while in the 17th century, the Manchu conquered China and established the Qing dynasty.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Islamic Mughal Empire (preceded by the Delhi Sultanate of the 13th to early 16th century) and the Hindu Maratha Empire controlled much of India in the 16th and 18th centuries respectively.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Western imperialism in Asia from the 18th to 20th centuries coincided with the Industrial Revolution in the West and the dethroning of India and China as the world's foremost economies.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Around this time, Western powers started to dominate China in what later became known as the century of humiliation, with the British-supported opium trade and later Opium Wars resulting in China being forced into an unprecedented situation of importing more than it exported.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] One significant influence on Japan had been the United States, which had begun projecting influence across the Pacific after its early-to-mid-19th century westward expansion.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The breakup of the Ottoman Empire in the early 20th century led to the Middle East also being contested and partitioned by the British and French.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] With the end of World War II in 1945 and the wartime ruination of Europe and imperial Japan, many countries in Asia were able to rapidly free themselves of colonial rule.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The independence of India came along with the carving out of a separate nation for the majority of South Asian Muslims, which in 1971 further split into Pakistan and Bangladesh; The Cold War in Asia strained relations between India and Pakistan and affected Asia more generally.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The end of the Cold War and the Soviet Union by 1991 saw the independence of the five modern Central Asian countries.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Some Arab countries took economic advantage of massive oil deposits that were discovered in their territory, becoming globally influential, though stability in the Middle East has been affected since 1948 by the Arab–Israeli conflict and American-led interventions.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] East Asian nations (along with Singapore in Southeast Asia) became economically prosperous with high-growth "tiger economies"; China, having undergone the reform and opening up under Deng Xiaoping, regained its place among the top two economies of the world by the 21st century.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] It covers 9% of the Earth's total surface area (or 30% of its land area), and has the longest coastline, at 62,800 kilometres (39,022 mi).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia is generally defined as comprising the eastern four-fifths of Eurasia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] It is located to the east of the Suez Canal and the Ural Mountains, and south of the Caucasus Mountains (or the Kuma–Manych Depression) and the Caspian and Black Seas.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] It is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia is subdivided into 49 countries, five of them (Georgia, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkey) are transcontinental countries lying partly in Europe.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Geographically, Russia is partly and mostly in Asia, but is considered a European nation, both culturally and politically.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Gobi Desert is in Mongolia and the Arabian Desert stretches across much of the Middle East.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Yangtze in China is the longest river in the continent.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The Himalayas between Nepal and China is the tallest mountain range in the world.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Tropical rainforests stretch across much of southern Asia and coniferous and deciduous forests lie farther north.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Between 1990 and 2000 the area of primary forest in Asia decreased by 1.06 million hectares per year, between 2000 and 2015 it decreased by 280 000 ha per year.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] There are various approaches to the regional division of Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The following subdivision into regions is used, among others, by the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] This division of Asia into regions by the United Nations is done solely for statistical reasons and does not imply any assumption about political or other affiliations of countries and territories.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia has extremely diverse climate features.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Climates range from Arctic and subarctic in Siberia to tropical in southern India and Southeast Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] It is moist across southeast sections, and dry across much of the interior.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Some of the largest daily temperature ranges on Earth occur in western sections of Asia.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The monsoon circulation dominates across southern and eastern sections, due to the presence of the Himalayas forcing the formation of a thermal low which draws in moisture during the summer.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Southwestern sections of the continent are hot.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Siberia is one of the coldest places in the Northern Hemisphere, and can act as a source of arctic air masses for North America.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The most active place on Earth for tropical cyclone activity lies northeast of the Philippines and south of Japan.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Climate change is particularly important in Asia, as the continent accounts for the majority of the human population.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Warming since the 20th century is increasing the threat of heatwaves across the entire continent.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Heatwaves lead to increased mortality, and the demand for air conditioning is rapidly accelerating as the result.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] By 2080, around 1 billion people in the cities of South and Southeast Asia are expected to experience around a month of extreme heat every year.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The impacts on water cycle are more complicated: already arid regions, primarily located in West Asia and Central Asia, will see more droughts, while areas of East, Southeast and South Asia which are already wet due to the monsoons will experience more flooding.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] The waters around Asia are subjected to the same impacts as elsewhere, such as the increased warming and ocean acidification.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] There are many coral reefs in the region, and they are highly vulnerable to climate change, to the point practically all of them will be lost if the warming exceeds 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia's distinctive mangrove ecosystems are also highly vulnerable to sea level rise.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Asia also has more countries with large coastal populations than any other continent, which would cause large economic impacts from sea level rise.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Water supplies in the Hindu Kush region will become more unstable as its enormous glaciers, known as the "Asian water towers", gradually melt.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] These changes to water cycle also affect vector-borne disease distribution, with malaria and dengue fever expected to become more prominent in the tropical and subtropical regions.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Food security will become more uneven, and South Asian countries could experience significant impacts from global food price volatility.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] Historical emissions from Asia are lower than those from Europe and North America.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] However, China has been the single largest emitter of greenhouse gases in the 21st century, while India is the third-largest.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] As a whole, Asia currently accounts for 36% of world's primary energy consumption, which is expected to increase to 48% by 2050.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] By 2040, it is also expected to account for 80% of the world's coal and 26% of the world's natural gas consumption.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] While the United States remains the world's largest oil consumer, by 2050 it is projected to move to third place, behind China and India.
[src:fargo-trucks/asia-p01] While nearly half of the world's new renewable energy capacity is built in Asia, this is not yet sufficient in order to meet the goals of the Paris Agreement.
